Italy balance

acarioli

04/02/2018

Using ISTAT data from 2016 one can make a few plots to look at how the population is distributed at subnational level. Being Italy a country with longstanding low fertility (=few births) and high longevity (=old population), its interesting to look at how the natural balance, that is to say the number of births minus the number of deaths), varies at subnational level.

dt <- read_csv(paste0(file,".csv")) %>% 
  select(c(1:16, 26:28)) %>% 
  gather(sex_type, value, 5:19) %>% 
  separate(sex_type, c("sex","type"), sep="_") 
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   .default = col_integer(),
##   area = col_character(),
##   regione = col_character(),
##   province = col_character(),
##   del_HHavnumber = col_double()
## )
## See spec(...) for full column specifications.
dt1 <- dt %>% 
  group_by(sex, type, regione, area) %>%
  summarise(value=sum(value))

  theme_bw()+
  theme(legend.position="none")+
  # guides(fill=guide_legend(title="Area"))+
  geom_col(aes(fill=as.factor(area)), width=.9)+
  coord_flip()+
  xlab("")+
  ylab("")

  coord_flip()+
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0)+
  theme(legend.position="none")
